{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":30547,"record_hash":"sha256:f065d894c48e75d047527c03167c942b23ad5d1821ea8d0c961ec7aefd161802","timestamp":"2026-05-11T17:05:45.575Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: agent-session-capture/agentlog-sync-lifecycle.md\n@@\n For the first implementation, add this in `git-meta` before wiring\n `but-agentlog sync`.\n \n+## GitMeta API Design Bias\n+\n+`SyncScope` should be a general GitMeta library concept, not an agentlog-only\n+special case. Other consumers should be able to define a named key scope, local\n+ref, remote ref, and key matcher without depending on GitButler vocabulary.\n+\n+At the same time, do not build a broad framework before there is pressure for\n+it. The first implementation should be rooted in the concrete agentlog use\n+case:\n+\n+- one named scope\n+- exact key matching\n+- one local ref and one remote ref\n+- scoped serialize/materialize bookkeeping\n+- normal Git fetch/push transport\n+- bounded non-fast-forward retry\n+\n+Prefer APIs that make this concrete use case easy to write correctly, then leave\n+additional routing, multiple scopes per command, custom merge policy, and extra\n+reporting for later.\n+\n ## Suggested Ref Shape\n \n Agentlog sync is key-scoped first. The serialized local ref and remote ref\n should mirror that scope as directly as GitMeta allows:\n@@\n ## Decided POC Choices\n \n - `but agentlog sync` is a full bidirectional sync command.\n - Do not add `--push-only` or `--pull-only` until there is a concrete need.\n - If `--remote` is omitted, use `origin`.\n - The key scope/ref suffix should match the local GitMeta name for agentlog.\n - Keep the implementation as normal GitMeta exchange: serialize, fetch,\n   materialize, and push. Do not add custom backend ingestion or product-specific\n   sharing behavior for the POC.\n+\n+## Implementation Milestones\n+\n+1. Add `SyncScope` to `git-meta`.\n+   - It should carry a name, local ref suffix/ref, remote ref suffix/ref, and a\n+     key matcher.\n+   - It should be general enough for non-GitButler callers.\n+\n+2. Add scoped sync bookkeeping in `git-meta`.\n+   - Track serialization/materialization state per scope or per serialized ref.\n+   - Keep the existing default/all-metadata lifecycle independent.\n+\n+3. Add scoped serialization in `git-meta`.\n+   - Serialize only keys matched by the `SyncScope`.\n+   - Write `refs/meta/local/<scope-name>` for the agentlog scope.\n+   - Do not mutate persistent filter rules to achieve this.\n+\n+4. Add scoped materialization in `git-meta`.\n+   - Materialize only keys matched by the `SyncScope`.\n+   - Missing keys outside the scope must not affect local SQLite state.\n+   - Missing remote ref means initial sync, not deletion.\n+\n+5. Add scoped push/fetch sync in `git-meta`.\n+   - Fetch `refs/meta/<scope-name>` into its matching tracking ref when it\n+     exists.\n+   - Push `refs/meta/local/<scope-name>` to `refs/meta/<scope-name>`.\n+   - Retry non-fast-forward with the boring fetch/materialize/serialize loop.\n+\n+6. Add `but agentlog sync` in GitButler.\n+   - Define the agentlog `SyncScope` with the exact key matcher.\n+   - Default `--remote` to `origin`.\n+   - Keep output terse and privacy-aware.\n+\n+7. Add focused validation.\n+   - GitMeta tests cover scoped bookkeeping, scoped materialization isolation,\n+     missing remote ref creation, and non-fast-forward retry behavior.\n+   - GitButler tests cover CLI parsing/output and one repo-to-repo agentlog\n+     exchange path without introducing a new reader layer.\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T17:05:45.575Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}